title: For Sale:  Russian RPK-74 Pro Built RPKS-74 Molot kit PLO
postcontent:
Selling a unfired professionally built Russian RPKS-74 in mint condition. This is chambered in 5.45x39mm.

This was built using a brand new 1985 dated Russian Molot front end (everything from the receiver forward including barrel.) This was built on a 5.45x39mm VEPR receiver in order to get a real Russian receiver. This worked out great and has factory features and spot welds, you just cant get more authentic than that. A military bullet guide was riveted in place and the insanely rare RPKS-74 folding stock was installed. The mix of a laminated buttstock and plum grip and handguards is correct for a 1986 vintage RPKS-74. This has the correct shiny Plum MOLOT grip, good luck finding one of those! This has a brand new cold hammer forged, chrome lined Russian barrel
 It was built by POHF to exacting specifications. The receiver has the correct selector marks and proper factory spot welds. The rifle uses the correct factory rivet pattern and has a paint over park finish, just like the Soviets. This is as accurate clone to a factory rifle as available. Only the receiver was refinished in an effort to keep as much as the factory finish as possible. Comes with one Molot 45 round mag were legal. The 6- US parts are trigger, hammer, sear, floorplate, follower, and Arsenal gas piston.

title: For Sale:  COLT 1911  MADE 1918  " with plexiglass pin up girl grips"
postcontent:
Offering a Colt 1911 Black Army  .45 ACP Pistol serial number 567485,1918 manufacture. 
the dark finish has been worn off largely due to the salty conditions of the South Pacific where this pistol saw service during WW2. Bore  is sharp and shiny.the S8 is clear on the left side of the frame.
as is the 12 on the trigger guard.
An interesting thing about this Colt are the cut-outs under the clear plastic-Plexiglas taken from the canopy of a Japanese
Zero aircraft.Each side with pin up girl pictures of the famous artist of the time period  Alberto Vargas. He became famous in the 1940s as the creator of iconic World War II era pin-ups for Esquire magazine known as "Vargas Girls." The nose art of many World War II aircraft was adapted from these Esquire pin-ups.  .
Some of these 1918 era 1911's were reissued during the Second World War, some came home after the first war.
It is a excellent   example  of how  our servicemen customized there issued firearms, what a  wonderful history, if only
it could talk.

You provide the land or property (must have a solid backstop, and be big enough to safely have 6 people on the shooting line at once - I will need to see the land before officially booking the date of course). You also provide the group - this can be anything from 20 people, to just a husband/wife that want to get some training without having a lot of strangers shooting right next to them. $75/person for the class. If you get a group of 6 OR MORE - YOUR class is free ($75 for everyone else). Class times will vary but plan for a 4-hour time-frame (if we run longer, there are no extra fees).

What you need:
1) Land with a solid backstop (could be a ridge, hill, large hay bails, dirt mounds, etc.)
2) Handgun of your choice and 500 rounds of ammo (may not shoot it all)
3) A date in mind with a 4 or 6 hours window (Saturday's work best)
4) A group of people (men or women) that want to invest in good, defensive training
5) An open mind

That's it. You don't need lots of experience. This can be very laid back and simple, or could be more advanced if that's what you decide - I tailor the course to you. I bring the targets and all training materials not listed above. I can schedule on your time (as long as the date is open). 

If you would like more information or would like to schedule, please contact me at:

Bryce Booher
Defensive Resources LLC

title: For Sale:  MultiPax Steel Shot Load Measure
postcontent:
This is a MultiPax Steel Shot Load Measure, used but in good working order.  This is a good working collectible!

The Multipax was offered by Reloading Specialties for about 5 years or so, right after steel shot became mandatory. It has two four inch tubs mounted on a stand. Each tub holds about 3lbs of shot. The two tub design was to make loading duplex loads easier. These tubs are fittled with adjustable disks in the bottom with holes in them. They are adjustable in the amount of holes that each hold one pellet. They have a crank handle on top and a spout on the bottom for dropping a charge of shot. Each 360 degree turn of the crank drops a given number of pellets. You can get a consistant number of pellets dropped with each crank. The disks that come with it each have different size holes to allow fitment of #4 thru T size steel shot.
When loading a 1 1/2oz load of #1 steel, it takes three cranks of the handle dropping 51 pellets each crank. It is very accurate and smooth operation using good quality polished steel shot. Dark colored, unpolished shot will cause hangups with the Multipax.

Call REDACTED or come by Green Country Arms & Pawn in Tulsa, OK, (9075 E 31st St, Tulsa, OK). Be sure to mention that you saw our ad on Armslist.

title: For Sale:  HK MR762A1
postcontent: The mr762A1 Like its 5.56 mm counterpart, the MR762A1 is a direct descendent of the HK416/417 series, only in a semi-automatic rifle configuration developed for civilian users. Using the HK-proprietary operating system, the MR762A1 is gas operated and uses a piston and a solid operating â€œpusherâ€ rod in place of the common gas tube normally employed in AR15/M16/M4-style weapons. Pioneered by Heckler & Koch in the G36, HK416, and HK417; this method virtually eliminates malfunctions common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. The MR762A1 stays cleaner, reducing heat transfer to the bolt and bolt carrier, and drastically reducing wear and tear on other critical components. The service life of all parts is increased substantially. The MR762A1 uses a barrel produced by Heckler & Koch's famous cold hammer forging process. This manufacturing process uses the highest quality steel, producing a barrel that ensures superior accuracy, even after firing thousands of rounds. The MR762A1 is produced at Heckler & Koch's American manufacturing facilities from both American and German-made components. The MR762A1 uses many of the assemblies and accessories originally developed for the HK416/417 series including adjustable buttstocks, ergonomic pistol grips, mechanical sights, and the HK free-floating four-quadrant rail system/handguard. This MIL-STD-1913 â€œPicatinnyâ€ type rail system allows all current accessories, sights, lights, and aimers used on M4/M16-type weapons to be fitted to the MR series. The HK rail system can be removed without special tools by the user and ensures 100% return to zero when reinstalled. Ambidextrous operating controls are standard on the MR762A1, including a convertible charging handle and an ambidextrous selector lever. The MR762A1 uses the same 10- and 20-round translucent polymer box magazines made for the HK417; a 5-round magazine is also under development. MR762A1 rifles are well-suited for a variety of applications including law enforcement tactical, police patrol, general sporting, and hunting (a 5-round magazine is under development).
